Trick Out Your Pinterest Boards With This Simple Hack
Click Here to find out more.

The first Pinterest user we've seen to "hack" his boards, digital development manager Nick McGlynn inspired us to have a go too. But what inspired him?
"My colleague and I were brainstorming ways to use Pinterest for brands at Rodale Inc and I noticed that the nine squares that make up the Pinterest boards make a perfect square that would fit Instagram photos brilliantly.
"I grabbed some Instagram photos from a recent Facebook Timeline 'hack' I did 
and decided to see how it would look if I cut them up into nine squares and made a Pinterest board."
We think they look great! Continue through the gallery for instructions on how to hack your boards.

Select a square photo you'd like to use. If you need to crop a pic square first, head over to 
Pixlr; its free "Express" photo editing tool offers a square crop option.
Now go to PicSlice, a free service that will slice up your image into nine neat squares.
If you are a Photoshop ninja, listen to MvGlynn's methodology: "I pulled the already square 450-pixel wide Instagram photo into Photoshop, then using the 'Slice' tool, I created 150-pixel square slices on the photo so it was cut into nine smaller square boxes. 
"I saved this as a Photoshop action so I could repeat the process easily for any other Instagram photo I wanted to upload. Then I saved the images in a folder."

Over on PicSlice, upload your photo via the "Choose File" button and click "Upload."\r\nClick on "Slice picture," which you'll see above your image. Now enter "3" into both the vertical slice and horizontal slice boxes. Click "Generate."

You can now save your nine images either by clicking on each image to download it, or by scrolling to the bottom, where you'll get the option the save the images in a ZIP file.\r\nThe photo files will be named numerically, for example, "1-xsxc6CSE9N."
Go to Pinterest and create a new board via the "Add" button.
Now click "Add" again and select "Upload a Pin."
Click "Choose File" and upload the images in reverse order, so start with photo nine and end with photo one. You'll have to "describe" each pin -- we just numbered ours.

And that's it! You should have a new Pinterest board comprised of nine small images that make up one big montage of awesomeness.\r\nDon't forget to link us to your boards in the comments below -- we can't wait to see what you create!
